Ask HN: Is it normal now to have the interviews spread over weeks?
text:
I have been interviewing with multiple companies during the last month, and one major difference I noticed compared to my last job search is that most companies now have multiple interviews spread over weeks, last time I did a job search it was usually a 1 hour screening interview/test followed up by half a day of interviews, but now 1h interview, then submit availability, then another 1h and so on, and you end up spending 4 weeks doing what you used to do in a day.

I don't understand how this is better than having the interviews in a single day, is it because of the volume of applicants this time around? or was it always like this but I got lucky before?

Ask HN: Free hosting companies are still a viable bussiness?
text:
I am just asking out of curiosity.

I was browsing old websites through Web Archive from 2004 and most of them had the banner that the free hosting provided included in your HTML (beautiful days!). I clicked in some of them and to my surprises, those websites are still working.

One example is this: http://www.freeservers.com

It seems it was stood in time (landing looks from 2006), but it is still working, so I wonder if this one is still a viable bussiness or what...

Show HN: Micro – Platform APIs built for developers
text:
Hey all,

Just reposting after about a year since the last time I shared. Micro is a platform for API development. It combines a lot of the core primitives you'd expect from a cloud platform as a single logical server. The closest equivalent is Dapr.io. It bakes in the concept of environments, source to running builds and a framework for Go development.

It's useful where you want to write backend services in Go and expose them through a single API (also included in Micro).

We once wrote about "Netlify for the frontend, Micro for the backend" https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=25068782 which went down well on HN. From a purely open source perspective my goal is to continue to evolve Micro as a community led effort, whereas previously I was trying to push for VC funding and building a product (been there, done that with M3O.com powered by Micro).

By sharing this I'm hoping to just shine a light on the upcoming trend of platform engineering and the need for platform APIs as part of the offering.

If this doesn't go down well, I'll write a more thoughtful blog post on platform APIs and how Micro/Dapr play a role in that.
